The convention of placing the operator between the operands is known as infix operator infix notation infix notation. It follows the mathematical notation that the reader is most likely familiar with from school and everyday life. As in mathematics, operator combinations can be nested, that is, they can have operands that nested operator combinations themselves are operator combinations:
(3 * 5) + (10 - 6);
19
As usual, parenthesesto group operator combinations parentheses are used to group operator combinations in order to avoid ambiguities. JavaScript also follows the usual conventions when parentheses are omitted; multiplication and division bind more strongly than addition and subtraction. For example,
3 * 5 + 10 / 2;
stands for
(3 * 5) + (10 / 2);
We say that * and / have precedenceoperatorsof operators higher precedence than + and -. Sequences of additions and subtractions are read from left to right, as are sequences of multiplications and divisions. Thus,
-as numeric subtraction operator - (numeric subtraction operator) -6
1 - 5 / 2 * 4 + 3;
stands for
(1 - ((5 / 2) * 4)) + 3;
We say that the operators +, -, * and / are associativityoperatorof operators left-associative left-associative.

There is no limit (in principle) to the depth of such nesting and to the overall complexity of the expressions that the JavaScript interpreter can evaluate. It is we humans who might get confused by still relatively simple expressions such as
57
3 * 2 * (3 - 5 + 4) + 27 / 6 * 10;
which the interpreter would readily evaluate to be 57. We can help ourselves by writing such an expression in the form
3 * 2 * (3 - 5 + 4) + 27 / 6 * 10;
to visually separate the major components of the expression.
